<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-01-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-01-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="370" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d370">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">713.1311/151</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Secretary of State (<persName corresp="#p_SHL1">Stimson</persName>)</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-01-05">January 5, 1933</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>During the call of the Guatemalan Minister I asked him about the
                            situation of Guatemala, expressing to him my gratification at the
                            Guatemalan support of the Treaty of 1923. The Minister told me that
                            although the Treaty had been renounced by Costa Rica and Salvador, the
                            other three countries acted to support it, and I said we would support
                            it so long as these Republics did. He then stated that Costa Rica really
                            stood as a nation apart from the others and her action did not make so
                            much difference.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">H[<hi rend="smallcaps">enry</hi>] L.
                                        S[<hi rend="smallcaps">timson</hi>]</persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>